I want to study social work and work for the Division of Family and Children Services. I will help children who have been hurt and support families that are having problems. Some important values for social work are service, respect, and helping others. It is important for me to keep learning to be good at my job. I always wanted to help people, but I was not sure which job to do. In high school and college, I saw people avoid their problems and use bad ways to deal with them. Because of these situations, I studied psychology. I was not sure what to do after college, so I took a break. One day, I met a boy who was escaping his bad parents. I helped him talk to the police. The police wanted me to talk to his parents. They said the boy was “manipulating” them. After this, I thought about working in social work to help families with small problems.

Another important value in social work is social justice. Society says each person is important, but we still try to be like everyone else. I am unique and do not like limits. In high school and college, I protested against social injustice. I did this by coloring my hair, wearing special clothes, and fighting against racism and discrimination. I will continue to fight for social justice.

This paper explains two models about insomnia: the biological and sociocultural models. The biological model focuses on genes and health problems. The sociocultural model looks at how people's surroundings affect sleep. This review of insomnia uses these models to better understand sleep problems.

Insomnia can be caused by many things, such as other health problems, medicines, or even sleep problems themselves. There are two main types of sleep problems: dyssomnias and parasomnias. Dyssomnias include problems like insomnia and narcolepsy. Parasomnias are sleep problems that cause strange behavior or physical changes, like nightmares or sleepwalking.

The biological model looks at genes and health problems. Orexin is a chemical in the brain that helps us sleep and stay awake. In mice, a study found that there are special receptors on orexin neurons that help control sleep and wakefulness. If these receptors don't work right, it can cause sleep problems. This study shows that sleep problems might be inherited, but it's also possible that they are caused by environmental factors.

The sociocultural model looks at how people's surroundings affect sleep. For example, people's race, ethnicity, age, and how much money they have can affect their sleep. This model can help us understand why some people have sleep problems and others do not.

Some studies have found that genes and health problems can cause sleep problems. However, other studies have shown that environmental factors can also cause sleep problems. Both models have strengths and weaknesses. The biological model can help us understand the physical causes of sleep problems, but it might not explain all of them. The sociocultural model can help us understand how people's surroundings affect sleep, but it might not explain the exact cause of sleep problems.

This paper talks about three parts of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it gives a short definition. Next, it explains how to diagnose it. Finally, it gives ways teachers can help students with CAPD in a regular classroom.

CAPD is a problem with how the brain uses sounds. People with CAPD can hear normally, but they have trouble understanding what they hear, like separating words or hearing sounds in space. This problem was first called "auditory imperception" in the 1950s. A national conference about this disorder was in 1977.

CAPD has many signs. People with this disorder may not hear sounds coming from different places. They may have trouble telling the difference between sounds. They may not understand sound patterns or changes in speech. They may also have trouble with sounds mixed together or sequences of sounds.

To diagnose CAPD, people take tests and answer questions. This is usually done by audiologists, speech-language pathologists, or psychologists. There is no single test used for this. Some tests use many sounds at once and ask people to pick out certain items. More advanced tests record sounds in the ear and measure how the brain responds.

Teachers can help students with CAPD in these ways:
- Make sure the classroom is quiet when students need to listen.
- Repeat or rephrase what you say to make sure the student understands.
- Break down lessons into small parts and give clear explanations.
- Use visuals like pictures or videos to help with understanding.
- Make sure the student is not distracted while listening.
- Give extra time for the student to answer questions.
- Check in with the student about what they understand during lessons.
- Work with the student's parents and other teachers to make sure they are getting help.

Twelfth Night says that while disguise can be useful for deception, it is important to stop the deception at some point to keep oneself. However, ending a deception can cause problems. Some people will not take it lightly and will be offended. In Twelfth Night, Viola pretends to be a man to protect herself in a foreign land. She works well, but it also makes her feel alone and causes problems with her feelings for Orsino. Olivia, who loves Cesario, thinks Cesario is a man. She also loves Sebastian when she sees him. Some people think this shows hidden feelings for women. But Olivia might just be looking at people based on their looks, as she quickly loves Sebastian instead.

German colonial rule had bad effects, especially in South West Africa. The government there did not teach many native people. Instead, missionaries were mostly responsible. The government taught Europeans better. This made a big difference in South West Africa, even after Germans left. Other colonies had more literate natives. This paper talks about why this happened. It looks at the attitudes of settlers and colonial leaders. There are many books about German colonial education. Early books were in German and were written around the time of German rule. Later, people wrote books in English that compared education in different colonies. A famous book by Cohen studied South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen said the many settlers in South West Africa made its education system different. South West Africa had a mild climate, and many Europeans lived there. In 1913, there were about 15,000 whites, while East Africa had only 5,336.

Popular music has many kinds. It is hard to list all genres. Most have many sub-genres. One popular type is heavy metal. It has many sub-genres and is very diverse. It shows many emotions, but dark ones. It started as a genre with flexibility. People made new sub-genres. Heavy metal is a movement, not just a genre. It has strong music and lyrics. It has dark, visceral qualities. It is like the Romantic Era. It started with songs like "Helter Skelter" by the Beatles. This song is considered the first heavy metal song.

Henri Rousseau wanted to be famous. He dreamed of people to like his paintings. He tried to make art that people liked. But, he also wanted to do his own thing. This was a problem. He wanted to be different. But, he also wanted to be accepted. This made him struggle a lot.

Rousseau was born in France. He was a worker. He was not educated in art. He lost his wife and children. So, he painted to feel better. He painted what he saw. He painted what he felt. He was a simple man. He wanted people to like his simple paintings.

Rousseau started painting later in life. He did not get famous until he was older. He was not like other artists. He did not follow rules. He did not want to be like Matisse. Matisse was famous. Rousseau was different. He wanted people to like him for being different.

Rousseau painted "The Dream" in 1910. This painting shows a woman looking at a dream. It also shows Rousseau's own dreams and thoughts. He dreamed of being famous. He dreamed of being liked. He dreamed of being unique. He wanted to be different. But, he also wanted to be accepted. This made him struggle.

Many great thinkers think that ethics and aesthetics are connected. I agree. John Keats said in "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty". We learn about ethics and aesthetics through education or experience. But we also understand them without learning. Both ethics and aesthetics try to explain good art or moral actions, not give rules. Critics cannot fully explain good art or morals. When we talk about a favorite work, we often say, "There's just something about it". Art and morals cannot be fully explained. Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way". Ethics has this same property. Wittgenstein says, "Ethics cannot be expressed. Ethics is transcendental". This "something" is art's and morality's power. It connects ethics and aesthetics. Morality and art affect us deeply. This is stronger with literature. McKean says, "Literature is unique. Its moral quality is important because we find values there".

Germany is a strong country today. It has a unique culture, from the mountains in Munich to the Baltic Sea in Kiel. This culture is also felt in cities like Cologne on the Rhine, Berlin in the center, and Dresden on the Elbe River.

Germany's name comes from the Germanic people. Many people think the name comes from a tribe called the Tungrians. This tribe was known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine River and fought with the Gauls. Others say the name comes from a spear used in battles, which was called a "ger," or from the Irish word "garim" meaning "to shout."

The early Roman historian Tacitus wrote about the Germans in his book "De Origine et situ Germanorum." He said the Germans were from the land and did not mix with other races. They lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded with them.

The Romans did not live in Germany. They sent their conquerors to get goods and lead military campaigns. The Germanic tribes lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded goods and services.

I looked at the view in front of me. I was not thinking. I was just looking. An artist told me about a book. The book is called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I wanted to learn to draw. This book helps me understand how to draw. The book teaches me how to use a square frame to look at pictures. It helps me see pictures in a simple way. When I looked at the bowl of fruit, I was too amazed. I could not use the square frame. I just stood and looked. It was like the start of a story. I had to clean the toilet. I tried to flush. I could not move the brown package. I had to clean it. I cleaned it with a mop. My hands and feet were dirty. I had to clean them. I stood up straight. I bent down. I put my hand into the bowl. I cleaned it. I finished.

Teenagers often die in car accidents. Several things happen together to cause this problem. The National Institutes of Health say the teen brain is not ready for driving. Teens are also new at driving. This causes more accidents, rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road.
Teens also have more accidents when they travel with friends. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center found this.
Some states have made teen drivers safer by limiting their driving hours and not letting other teens ride with them. But these rules are not enough. The youngest drivers are bad at handling risks and responsibilities.
Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman says even 18 is too young for a regular driver's license. He thinks teens under 19-20 like to take risks.
If we give driver's licenses to young teens, more accidents will happen. Millions of new teen drivers will be on the road by 2010.
Schools could teach driving, but no one under 18 could drive alone. A permit could be given before a full license, with some training hours required, like in California.
Legislation could make teen driving safer. This idea is not new.

In the Library of Congress, I looked at early Edison films. There were fifteen trick films from 1895 to 1901. I watched them all. These films use creative editing to make illusions. I studied the poetics of most trick films and the unusual characteristics of some later films. Most trick films at the turn of the century are set-bound. They are in a frontal proscenium. There is no camera movement. They use long and medium shots. They follow the one shot = one film rule. However, some early twentieth-century films break these rules with multiple shots.
All trick films have a common feature. They are filmed in an interior set within a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move. Figures in trick films move side-to-side, not towards or away from the camera. In Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors enter from the right and move back and forth. They go out of the frame, but the camera does not follow.
Long and medium shots are common in trick films. Close-ups are not used. This comes from the theatre and vaudeville traditions. A single conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of trick films to about a minute or less. Most trick films are short vaudeville tricks, like magic and disappearing acts. In trick films, one conceptual shot can be several physical shots combined to make an illusion. For example, in The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), the audience sees one conceptual shot, but a second physical shot is used to create the illusion of Mary's severed head.

John Taylor from Caroline was early and strong supporter of the Republican Party. As an agriculturalist and short-lived politician, he became known for his love of personal freedom and strong government. His beliefs about farming helped him form his views on government. He wanted to keep and grow a good system.

Taylor believed the United States had a chance to make a perfect system. There was no old tradition to stop it. He thought people had natural rights, and if one was taken, others would fail. These rights should not be controlled by the government. He thought only strong people with bad intentions benefited in a natural state, but in a civilization, it should not be this way.

To create a perfect society, Taylor said a government must consider the good and evil in people. He thought government decisions should protect personal property, help farming, and stop big business. He believed a good government would work well even with bad leaders. He thought self-interest was bad only when it hurt others. A good government must control this evil. It must also keep watch to stop bad rules.

Taylor, like many Republicans, wanted a strict constitution. He wanted a small federal government with only the powers listed in the constitution. He knew a big government could be bad. But he thought a simple reading of the constitution could be dangerous. He thought the Declaration of Independence was the true charter of the United States. It said the country was made of many states, not one nation.

Looking back at Figure 17, commuter log submissions fell quickly in the third month. This was disappointing, and no clear reason is known. Winter and schoolwork may cause the drop. December end of semester and holidays also affect commuting. The project had a big start, but normal decreases in interest and holiday breaks are common. To fix this, we created the Carpool Challenge Week in March, which helped. The challenge was keeping momentum with natural drops in engagement, and holiday and semester breaks. Another issue is people like driving cars. We gave gifts to encourage alternative transport, like bicycle, hybrid, or electric car. If the prizes were bigger, engagement might have increased. It was not clear if bigger prizes or more varied prizes helped.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, follows an index, commodity, or group of assets. It trades on an exchange like a stock. ETFs offer diversification and stock benefits. You can sell short, buy on margin, and buy as few as one share. ETFs have lower fees than mutual funds. However, you pay a commission for each trade. There are many types of ETFs. It's good to check if stated benefits, like diversification, are real.

To compare an ETF, we will look at the top 10 holdings. These holdings make up 63.58% of the ETF's assets. Here are the top 10 holdings and their percentages.

To check if the top 10 holdings represent the ETF well, we calculated their contribution to a portfolio's Beta and return. The portfolio's return is 6.11% higher than the ETF's return. The portfolio's Beta is lower. A portfolio of the top 10 holdings seems better, but this is not sure yet.

To check if the portfolios are different, we calculated the standard deviation of each top 10 stock. The standard deviation of the portfolio is higher than the ETF's. This means the portfolio is riskier.

So, the portfolio of the top 10 holdings might offer higher returns and lower risk, but more study is needed.

Edgar Allan Poe called "Dream-Land" one of his favorite poems. In this poem, he uses the word "Thulé." This word comes from Virgil, who used it for a place north of Britain. Poe also knew German writers. Karl J. Arndt says Poe's "Dream-Land" is like Goethe's "Mignon." In "Mignon," a king drinks and dies after losing his wife. Poe's poem has similar scenes. Poe uses "Thulé" twice, like bookends. "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" are like companion poems. The speaker in "Dream-Land" describes a dark, lonely place with no color. This could be the king's story. Poe knew Goethe's work through Tennyson's respect for him.

Under California law, can a customer hurt after slipping on an applesauce spill in a store get punitive damages? The customer can show the store manager did not clean the spill quickly because he knew about it and was eating dinner. But a judge will not dismiss the case quickly. The customer must show the manager's actions were bad and showed no care for others. The manager was told about the spill twice and did not clean it for 30 minutes. Before, five people slipped and fell at the store. The manager’s actions are bad, but this is not clear. California law allows punitive damages if the defendant acted with “oppression, fraud or malice.” The customer must show the manager’s actions were bad. Six people slipped at the store in 2009, and the manager did not clean the spill. The manager did not show care for others. The customer’s claim is strong. The judge will not dismiss the case quickly. The customer will get a chance to argue for punitive damages.

Four years ago, I studied Islam at CBC. We discussed if it is a hostile religion. This is more important today. After 9/11, media changed views. We could not have had a Muslim president like Barack Obama in 2001. The Prophet Muhammad's biography seems false. It says he was humble and kind, but he forced people to become Muslim. This is different from Jesus' teachings. The stories of Muhammad's miracles are similar to Jesus'. This makes me think they want to take credit for Jesus' life. Many stories are not from Muhammad himself. They make the stories seem less true. The biography tries to show Muhammad as a kind and wise man, but history says he was not. This makes me think Muslims do not know the truth about Muhammad's power.

The teachings of Jesus had a long history in Christian thought. Over time, the beliefs moved away from their origin. Today, people show great progress in understanding. Traditional people resist new ideas. But they may not have big influence. In the future, many Christians will learn more about Christian history. They will want to find the true teachings of Jesus. This will lead to a big change in Christianity. People will remove added beliefs. They will go back to what Jesus taught. The church will be strong, but beliefs will become more uniform. People will see more similarities between different groups. History shows that big changes can happen. For example, Christianity once faced persecution by Rome. Now it is strong in many countries. African Americans went from slavery to leadership. The future will bring a big change in Christianity. People will read Jesus' words as metaphors, not just literal statements. What happened to Christianity since Jesus lived?

I believe The Jungle shows how people are naturally greedy and self-centered. They want to make their own lives better, but do not care about others. The owners and managers of big factories only want to make their companies big. They do not care about pollution or workers. They make their factories big, with smoke and waste. They force workers to work long hours and can fire them suddenly. There were no safety laws, so the managers could do what they wanted. The workers had no help. Unions did not help the workers. Workers were like slaves. They lived and worked in bad conditions.

Many writers use special methods to make readers feel or think about important things. One of these methods is using an unusual pair of words, like an adjective and a noun, to make a subject feel different. Another method is using symbols that stand for special meanings, and then using these symbols again to make readers remember a feeling. In his novel "The Great Gatsby," F. Scott Fitzgerald uses these methods with colors like gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. He makes the colors stand for certain feelings and then uses them to show readers what to think about important things.

Fitzgerald makes white/gray stand for uniformity, with white being nicer and gray being older and faded. In the start of the novel, people are always wearing white: Daisy and Jordan are "in white" (8), Nick wears "white flannels" (41), Tom wears a "white shirt" (36), and Catherine is "powdered milky white" (30). Even common things are shown as white or gray: Nick goes "down the white chasms of lower New York" (56), the names on Nick's timetable are "gray names" (61), and the dog-seller is "a gray old man" (27).

After giving white/gray their meanings, Fitzgerald uses them to show readers that Daisy is only a simple, uniform thing that Gatsby wants. This starts when Daisy is described as "dressed in white" in "a little white roadster" (74). Fitzgerald uses more of this method to make Daisy feel like a uniform thing, for example, "Daisy's fur collar" is "a gray haze" (18), and she is "in a white dress" (115) before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County is good for farming because it has a mild, sunny climate. Common crops here are tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a big market for organic food. Many people want organic eggs and milk. Organic farms offer tours and activities like hiking and birdwatching.

Organic farming has good things, like more biodiversity. However, it costs more. It needs more work to remove pests and weeds, and the losses are often bigger. Small farms are not as efficient as big ones. But, the landowner can get help from government programs to make money and protect the environment.

The land chosen for this plan is 160 acres near Potrero in San Diego County. It has chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland. It is near the Cleveland National Forest. This land was home to Native Americans for a long time. Then, it was used for ranching and selling wood. It was part of an original homestead patent.

A small farmer can get help from government programs to make farming easier and cheaper. This can help the farmer make more money and protect the environment.

Culture is important in any negotiation. It is not the same for everyone. It can change. We should not make generalizations about culture. For example, not all Russians are stubborn, and not all Japanese are accommodating. We should think about how culture affects negotiations. When we meet a new culture, we should compare it to our own culture. This helps us understand it better. We should study the history and beliefs of a culture, not judge or change it. We should respect traditions and beliefs. If we are in a weaker position, this is extra important. Culture is not just about countries. Many companies have their own culture. This affects how people work and communicate. We should learn about our opponent's personal values to make the negotiation go well.

The Bible and some philosophers talk about God. Two famous ones are St. Anselm and St. Thomas Aquinas. They both believe God exists. We need to compare their arguments.

St. Anselm believes God is in our minds. He says we cannot think of God not existing. He thinks believing in God is like believing in something true. He calls this faith.

St. Thomas Aquinas thinks God can be proven using reason. He has five arguments. He says God is needed to explain changes, causes, and degrees of excellence.

Both have good points. But neither fully proves God exists.

A long time ago, in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born. He later became known as Buddha. He left his kingdom and became enlightened. His teachings are the basis for Buddhism. The Theravada section of Buddhism is about twenty-five hundred years old. Today, it looks different than when Buddha was alive.

In Sri Lanka, a Theravada country, the annual water-cutting ceremony is held. Monks and laypeople join. This ceremony has some religious meaning, although Buddha never taught about it. The Theravada Buddhist community has changed over time. This happened because of outside and inside forces, both good and bad.

We will use some special words in this talk. We will say 'inside' for people who are part of Buddhism, and 'outside' for people who are not. 'Hostile' means people who harm or want to harm Buddhism. 'Benign' means people who do not want to harm or help Buddhism. These words will be used often.

First, we must understand the core teachings of Buddhism. Buddhists seek help from the Triple Gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is made up of the Tripitaka, the three baskets of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka has all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka has the rules for life, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka has the metaphysical parts of Buddhism. Metaphysical ideas include Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (everything is impermanent). Recognizing these can end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth. This also ends lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion) when someone becomes enlightened. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules to live by. For laypeople, there are five rules: do not kill, do not lie, do not steal, do not misbehave sexually, and do not use intoxicating substances. Monks have many more rules. The most important teaching in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths: life is suffering, attachment causes suffering, suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico had a long fight. This lasted from 1836 to 1893. The big fight was the Mexican-American War in 1846-1848. The United States won and took land. Many other fights happened between the two countries. The fight ended before World War I.
Both countries had many disputes. They had problems about religion, culture, and money. They were not like other countries. Many other countries had good relations with the United States.
The fight started because of religious and cultural differences. Americans liked Protestantism and Mexico liked Catholicism. This was a big problem. The fight also started because of the Spanish and English who had bad feelings about each other.
Diehl and Goerts wrote about 17 fights between Mexico and the United States from 1836 to 1893. Most fights were about land. Mexican bandits and outlaws made problems. Schmitt said the fight ended because Mexico was weak and the United States wanted money, not land.

Fifteen years ago, I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. I was a nurse at the time. I chose nursing because it was a safe job. I heard, "People will always get sick," so I thought it would always have work. I dreamed of being a scientist or journalist, but I chose nursing instead.

I was 46 years old and single. I had no money in the bank and could not work. I am still disabled. After 15 years on Social Security Disability, I have nothing left. Every day is a struggle. My life is not certain, but my family and friends helped me through it.

Life has many emergencies. Some are small, but some are too big to overcome alone. We should trust each other and help each other, not build individual shelters.

Conservatives in the US talk about "rugged individualism." But our forefathers crossed the Rockies in wagon trains, not alone. They helped each other.

Be prepared. I have a disaster kit, first aid supplies, water purifying tablets, and flashlights. I also have food and heat sources. But also, get to know your neighbors.

Why do organisms change over time? Are there limits that affect how they change? D’Arcy Thompson said in 1917 that scientists did not understand organic forms. Now, mathematic models are used to study mollusk skeletogenesis. Our study combines math and experiments to see how Prunum changes. We used X-ray images to find shell shapes. Mathematical software helped us model possible changes. We combined our results with experiments to understand big evolutionary changes.

A shell is like a tube that grows in a spiral. Whorls are these spirals. The center column is the columella. The largest whorl is the body whorl. The spire is all the whorls except the body whorl. The tip is the apex. The base is the opposite end. The animal exits the shell through the aperture.

Shells can be seen from different views: apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural. The usual view is apertural, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing up.

To count whorls, first, view the shell from the apical side. Find the first suture line. Draw a line dividing the shell. Count the whorls from this line, estimating a quarter whorl.

A shell is like a series of openings that move through time and space. We can trace this path and make a mathematical model. Once we have a model, we can change parameters to see how skeletogenesis changes.

In Indonesia, many babies and mothers die before turning one. This has not changed much in the last ten years. Indonesia is close to meeting some goals, but not child and mother health goals. The reasons are many. We need to fix the health system, not just make small changes in programs.

Indonesia is doing well with births with a skilled worker. 72% meet this goal. But, traditional workers like midwives cannot help with complicated pregnancies. So, many mothers die from bleeding.

Diarrhea treatment is also a problem. Few children under five get help from a health professional. Post-birth care is not done well.

Cesarean deliveries are low, at 4%. This rate is even lower in rural areas. This shows that healthcare is better in cities.

The rich use healthcare more than the poor. This is because the poor have to pay a lot for care.

To help babies and mothers, we need to fix the entire health system or only focus on one program. Focusing on one program may be easy, but it can cause other problems. For example, money for other care may be less. And, different programs may have the same services. This causes more work for workers.

Victorian novels are known for their detailed focus on the aristocracy. Two exceptions are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. These books use mystery and unusual events to make the characters more interesting. They also show the characters' feelings and reasons for their actions.

For example, in Oliver Twist, the main character has strange dreams and experiences that show his feelings and thoughts. After his shooting, he has vivid dreams about the event. This shows that he feels powerless and scared. He cannot control what happens to him. He also feels defeated, like his life is not his own. This makes the reader understand Oliver's feelings better.

Two years ago, I worked in an after-school program. I helped students in many subjects, but I was good at English and reading. A teacher asked me to help a boy named Adrian. He was having trouble reading. I found out he did not know the English alphabet. He spoke perfect English, but some letters were hard for him. I told this story to show that language barriers can be hard in schools, especially in California. Even a child who speaks good English can have reading problems. The solution is not easy. For Adrian, tutoring in English reading helped. But for children who speak little English, there is no one answer. We need to use many methods together, like the dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, and ESL classes.

In the dual language system, children learn two languages, like Spanish and English. This can help all children, not just those who speak Spanish. But some people think it is a waste of resources. They think only some students will benefit. This is not true. If we make this system the rule, all children will benefit. We do not need all teachers to be bilingual. But we can have special helpers who speak two languages.

From young, many people learn about things bigger than themselves. Some go to church or temple. Others look inside themselves for answers. Some believe in passed-down religions. Others reject them. They search for light in darkness. They want to find meaning. My father, when I asked, said his favorite bird was a cardinal. We sat on the porch. He talked about his life. He showed me what was important. He died in December. Chemo and radiation did not help. I could not watch. I wanted to remember him as he lived, not how he died. I waited alone for news. No one called me.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is an "old-new" combination, as Ian Watt says in "The Rise of the Gothic Novel." People like and dislike Gothic novels. They are praised for their "terrible sublime" feeling (Burke). The first Gothic novel, "The Castle of Otranto" by Horace Walpole, mixed old and new ideas. It used old theater and nature in new novels. The Gothic genre often uses medieval styles and ideas. Even in Walpole's time, the word "gothic" meant many things. It was seen as old-fashioned. The mix of old Gothic and new novels made Gothic popular and new to readers far away in time.

One big Gothic idea is Chivalry. It is from the medieval time when knights were trained. Walpole's "The Castle of Otranto" uses this idea. It shows the old idea of a brave and honorable knight. Walpole wrote this during a time of political trouble. He was unhappy with his society. He may have thought the goodness of the old Gothic era was gone. This is shown in some characters, like Frederic. Before meeting Frederic, he seems like a chivalrous knight. He is a prince, has suffered, and his death is supposed to be by infidels. He is also called a "gallant and courteous Knight," with excessive features (Walpole 66).

Supply chain management is the process of moving goods from customer orders to the end. The term was first used in 1982 by Keith Oliver, a consultant. He said it is about planning, doing, and controlling the steps to meet customer needs quickly and well.

There are six parts to a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these parts to give good service to customers.

Production is the first step. It starts the whole process. Managers need to know what customers want. They can look at the market to decide this. After knowing customer needs, managers decide what to produce and how much. Then they choose where to make it. They must think about what customers want and how to satisfy them.

Managers also plan work and equipment. Production is important. Every detail must be planned carefully. For example, I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target. Both companies have rules and plans for every part of their business. Having these plans helps the company work smoothly.

The second part is supply. Supply means making important decisions about what a facility can do and who to work with. A company may make many parts for a product. Each part needs different things. Managers must choose the best fit. They may also choose to work with other companies to save money and be flexible.

Hitler is alive in Burma, the sign says.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner with a sign. The message is written on the sign with a Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a country in Southeast Asia. The government is ruled by a military group. They took power in 1962. They do not allow protests.

In 2007, many monks protested peacefully. The protests were called the Saffron Revolution because the monks wore robes of that color. The government allowed the monks to gather peacefully at first. But then the protests became violent. The military attacked monasteries. A Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai was killed. The official death toll is 13, but Colonel Hla Win says thousands were killed.

This is not new. Many governments have tried to control their people. Early Roman emperors said they were chosen by gods. Japanese emperors are believed to be gods. President George W. Bush talks to Ted Haggard, leader of Stupid People Worldwide, every week.

Some examples are the protests at Tiananmen Square in 1989 and the Rwandan genocide in the 1990s. Hitler's Third Reich killed Jewish people.

Duke Ellington is important in jazz music because he played the piano for a long time. This helped him create many good songs. He wrote music that showed the skills of his band members. He let soloists play freely and created music that sounded good. He also wrote music that sounded new and interesting.

Ellington used the voice as an instrument in his music. In a song called "Creole Love Call", he did this by having the voice and the reeds (a group of instruments that make high, smooth sounds) play together. They started with a smooth sound, then changed to a rougher sound. He wrote many songs like this.

In "Hot and Bothered", Ellington used a different instrument, the trumpet, to make a call and response with a singer. He made the sounds of the trumpet and the voice work together to create a good sound. He did this again in a song called "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)".

Ellington wrote many songs that showed his skills and creativity. He used his band members' sounds to make his music interesting and new.

She had never felt she needed something. This desire continued for three years. It started when she was 14 and got into teenage life. By 17, she wanted someone, not a thing. No boys appealed to her, even though some tried. She wondered why this happened to a teenage girl. She thought about theories, but none seemed good enough. So, she lived life, always questioning her desires.

A normal day at home was peaceful. Her parents were calm and never argued. They only argued about her independence. She was likeable, fun, and kind. Today, though, was not calm. She heard a scream from the kitchen. She ran to help her mother. Her mother was in pain, lying on the ground. Her daughter helped her to the car and drove to the hospital.

The hospital smelled of cleaners and sickness. She was worried but focused on helping her mother. Doctors took her mother away. Her mother had fallen off a step stool trying to get a vase.

This study showed that eating a Mediterranean diet, as measured by a high score on the alternate Mediterranean diet (aMed), can reduce the risk of heart disease and stroke. The aMed diet includes more plant foods, like fruits, nuts, and whole grains, and less animal products and saturated fats. It also allows moderate alcohol. Previous studies showed the Mediterranean diet could help with weight loss and cholesterol levels.

This study followed 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, for 20 years. They answered food frequency questionnaires six times. These questionnaires were used to measure nutrient intake. The study also considered other factors, like age, smoking, and physical activity. The women's health was checked many times.

The researchers found that women who ate the Mediterranean diet had less heart disease and stroke. They used a statistical method called Cox proportional-hazard modeling to see the link between the diet and health risks. Women who ate the diet more were at lower risk for heart disease and stroke.

After 20 years, 2391 people had heart disease, 1763 had stroke, and 1077 died from heart disease or stroke. Women who ate the Mediterranean diet the most had a lower risk of heart disease and stroke than those who ate it the least.

In 2007, the United States of America had a big financial problem. Many people lost their jobs and big companies had big problems. This problem still exists. How did this happen and how can we stop it?

The crisis started because banks and companies made bad decisions. They gave loans to people who could not pay them back. This was called a sub-prime loan. They also sold these loans to each other in a complicated way.

The problem started in 1999 when the Clinton administration relaxed lending rules. This made it easier for people to get loans. But this also made the financial system weak. Steven Holmes of the New York Times said this could cause trouble in the future.

Many things combined to cause the crisis. One was the new type of mortgages. These mortgages were adjustable, meaning the interest rate could change. This made people and companies risk too much money in the housing market. When the housing market crashed, the banks and companies had big problems.

In 2007, the top five U.S. investment banks had $4.1 trillion of mortgage debts. This was about 30% of the USA's GDP. Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold cheaply. Lehman Brothers was dismantled. Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley became commercial banks. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac had $5 trillion of mortgage debt and were put under government control in September 2008.

Exposition is part of a story where you start to tell about the characters and their background. Some writers, like Dr. Merlin, get lost in exposition and write too much. It is better to show the story through actions and character development rather than just tell.

Show, don't tell is a writing tip that means to use actions and dialogue to reveal character and plot. Exposition is the opposite, where you just tell the reader what happened.

For example, if a story says a couple met and got married, you should show how they met and fell in love, not just say it. This helps the reader feel connected to the characters.

As a writer, you need to show the reader about the characters and their past. Sometimes it is easy to rush past details, like a character's history or favorite food. Instead, show the reader through actions and words what makes the character unique.

I saw two news reports from Columbus, Ohio. The first was from NBC 4, live today (August 13, 2011). It showed a man, Shad Hostettler, who had stabbed his wife in Ashley, Ohio. They showed his picture and said he looked evil. They talked about the story for two minutes. I think this was the right amount of time.

The second story was about a 18-year-old man, Travis Buyers, who was shot in Sharon Woods. He was hurt very badly. No one was arrested yet. The SWAT Team was investigating. This story was short. I think this might be because Travis is black, or the area is black. I have seen this before. If a white person is a victim, the news talks about it a lot. But if a black person is a victim, it is lucky if it is even mentioned.

The next story was about a bullet hole in a Med-Flight helicopter. They said the bullet was from a .22 caliber rifle. Crime-Stoppers are giving a five-thousand dollar reward for information. The next story was about rain and thunderstorms coming on Saturday. They said the temperatures would stay in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. They kept this short to make viewers stay tuned.

They also talked about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF. A black man robbed the store. They said he was tall and wore dark clothes. They talked about this a lot. The next story was about a man, Rene Rodriguez, who was a drug kingpin in Texas. He was sentenced to 300 months in prison for selling drugs. They said he was a Hispanic man, but I don't think that was important to the story.

A brother-brother relationship is special. It is strong and cannot be broken. Many feelings are in this bond: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers understand each other more than anyone else. They can see themselves in their brother. When bad things happen, the bond shows. It shows good or evil. This bond has a high cost. To understand the bond, one must deal with the feelings and their effects.

"The Scarlet Ibis" shows this bond. Two brothers go on a journey. They have many feelings. One brother dies. The story is about feelings of pride and disappointment. The main character has a lot of pride. He wants a brother to play with. He wants to teach him many things. But his brother is weak. He cannot play. The main character gets angry. He thinks about killing his brother. But then his brother smiles. The main character feels love. He does not do it.

The brain is a complex system for processing information. As technology changed, so did the ways we describe the brain. We first compared it to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, a book, and now to a computer. Remember, these descriptions are not perfect and can lead to wrong ideas.
Information starts with signals from our senses. These turn physical things like touch, heat, sound, and light into electrical signals. The brain processes these signals in two ways: bottom-up and top-down. For example, when seeing a black box on white paper, bottom-up helps us see it as a box. Top-down helps us know it is a box, not a hole. The results of processing are often changed by attention.
To process information, the brain must store it. There are three types of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. Information is first put into memory with special codes. For example, words can be stored by how they look, sound, or mean. Working memory stores info for 20 seconds. Long-term memory might be stored in proteins.
Many models help us understand how the brain organizes knowledge. One model is the semantic network. It says there are nodes for ideas, and that they are linked based on how related they are. For example, "chair" might be linked to "table" and "wooden".

Aldous Huxley criticizes technology and the capitalistic structure in Brave New World. People here value community above the individual. They are conditioned to seek happiness from the start. The citizens are pawns in a game, controlled by the World Controller. Huxley uses Marxist ideas to show problems in the economy. He uses terms like "homogeny" and "reification" to show this.

Capitalism is shown as using "false consciousness." People do not know their true economic relations. They are only interested in their own gain. The World Controller controls this. The lower classes, like Deltas and Gammas, have no will of their own. They are told to spend and indulge. The upper classes know about this, but do not do much. Interactions between classes show the oppression of capitalism.

In Brave New World, relationships are not real. Characters lack depth. Perhaps Huxley shows that technology and capitalism take away free will and expression. Love and strong emotions do not exist. People talk about each other in a superficial way. They are happy to keep their place in society. This shows the effect of capitalism.

I have lived at University Park for two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Walking to classes is hard. My first year, I lived in East Halls, far from most classes. To get to Willard building, it could take 25 minutes. Now, I live off campus. My house is far from the center. I have a bike now. Riding it takes 5 minutes to get to Thomas building, my main class. I could walk instead, but it takes 30-40 minutes, too long. A bike is better. More students need to bike. The campus needs to help bicyclists.
